# ==============================================================================
# ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES - EXAMPLE FILE
# ==============================================================================
#
# This is a template showing what environment variables this app needs.
# Environment variables are configuration values that:
#   1. Contain sensitive information (API keys, secrets)
#   2. Change between environments (development vs production)
#   3. Should NOT be committed to version control
#
# HOW TO USE THIS FILE:
#   1. Copy this file and rename it to ".env"
#   2. Replace the placeholder values with your real credentials
#   3. NEVER commit the .env file to Git (it's in .gitignore)
#
# Example:
#   cp .env.example .env
#   then edit .env with your real values
#
# ==============================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FIREBASE CONFIGURATION
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Get these values from your Firebase project:
#   1. Go to https://console.firebase.google.com
#   2. Sign in and select your project (or create a new one)
#   3. Click the gear icon (Settings) > Project settings
#   4. Scroll down to "Your apps" section
#   5. If no web app exists, click "Add app" > Web
#   6. Copy the firebaseConfig values
#
# IMPORTANT NOTE:
# The firebase.ts file has fallback values for the POCHOCLO project.
# These environment variables are optional but recommended for:
#   - Switching between projects easily
#   - Keeping credentials separate from code
#   - Following best practices
#

# Firebase API Key
# This identifies your project to Firebase services
# It's NOT a secret - Firebase Security Rules protect your data, not this key
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your-api-key-here

# Firebase Auth Domain
# Used for sign-in operations (popups, redirects on web)
# Format: your-project-id.firebaseapp.com
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project-id.firebaseapp.com

# Firebase Project ID
# Your unique project identifier
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id

# Firebase Storage Bucket
# Where files are stored (for Firebase Storage)
# Format: your-project-id.appspot.com or your-project-id.firebasestorage.app
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project-id.firebasestorage.app

# Firebase Messaging Sender ID
# For push notifications (Firebase Cloud Messaging)
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your-sender-id

# Firebase App ID
# Unique identifier for this specific app in your project
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your-app-id

# Firebase Measurement ID (Optional)
# For Google Analytics - can be omitted if not using analytics
EXPO_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MEASUREMENT_ID=your-measurement-id

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPORTANT NOTES
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# 1. EXPO_PUBLIC_ PREFIX:
#    In Expo, environment variables MUST start with EXPO_PUBLIC_ to be
#    accessible in your app code. This is a security feature.
#
# 2. SECURITY:
#    - The .env file is in .gitignore (won't be committed to Git)
#    - Never share your .env file publicly
#    - Firebase API keys are safe for client-side use (mobile apps)
#    - Security is enforced by Firebase Security Rules, not by hiding keys
#    - Never expose service account keys in client code
#
# 3. DEVELOPMENT vs PRODUCTION:
#    You might have different values for different environments:
#    - .env.development (for local development)
#    - .env.production (for production builds)
#    For now, one .env file is fine for learning!
#
# 4. RESTARTING THE APP:
#    After creating/modifying .env, restart your Expo dev server:
#    - Stop the current server (Ctrl+C)
#    - Run "npm start" again
#    Environment variables are loaded when the dev server starts
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# WHERE TO FIND YOUR FIREBASE CREDENTIALS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Step-by-step guide:
#
# 1. Create a Firebase account (if you haven't):
#    - Go to https://console.firebase.google.com
#    - Sign in with your Google account
#
# 2. Create a new project (or use existing):
#    - Click "Create a project" or "Add project"
#    - Enter project name (e.g., "pochoclo")
#    - Choose whether to enable Google Analytics (optional)
#    - Wait for project to set up
#
# 3. Add a Web app to your project:
#    - In project overview, click the web icon (</>)
#    - Enter an app nickname (e.g., "Pochoclo Web")
#    - Don't check "Firebase Hosting" for now
#    - Click "Register app"
#
# 4. Get your credentials:
#    - After registering, you'll see the firebaseConfig object
#    - Copy each value to the corresponding variable in your .env file
#    - Or go to Project Settings > Your apps > SDK setup and configuration
#
# 5. Enable Authentication:
#    - Go to Authentication > Sign-in method
#    - Enable "Email/Password" provider
#    - Click Save
#
# 6. Create your .env file:
#    - Copy this file: cp .env.example .env
#    - Open .env
#    - Replace the placeholder values with your real values
#    - Save the file
#
# 7. Restart your app:
#    - Stop Expo (Ctrl+C in terminal)
#    - Run: npm start
#    - Your app can now connect to Firebase!
#
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# FIREBASE VS SUPABASE - KEY DIFFERENCES
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# SUPABASE (old):
# - 2 variables: URL and Anon Key
# - URL format: https://xxxxx.supabase.co
# - Key is a long JWT token
#
# FIREBASE (new):
# - 7 variables (but all from one config object)
# - Simpler values (project IDs, domain names)
# - API key is NOT a secret (different from Supabase anon key concept)
#
# SECURITY MODEL:
# - Supabase: Row Level Security (RLS) policies in database
# - Firebase: Security Rules for Firestore, Storage, RTDB
#
# Both use the API key to identify the project, then apply security rules
# to determine what data the user can access.
